prob": 0.9972793459892273, "span": {"begin": 722, "end": 731}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5727"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PTCH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.5883192420005798, "span": {"begin": 731, "end": 735}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6608"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SMO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9902991056442261, "span": {"begin": 775, "end": 778}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3280", "9910"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HH ligand", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7660001516342163, "span": {"begin": 785, "end": 794}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5727"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PTCH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9899358153343201, "span": {"begin": 804, "end": 808}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6608"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SMO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.992371678352356, "span": {"begin": 825, "end": 828}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6608"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SMO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9741021394729614, "span": {"begin": 845, "end": 848}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6608"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SMO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9976881742477417, "span": {"begin": 996, "end": 999}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SHH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9888255000114441, "span": {"begin": 1066, "end": 1069}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5727"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PTCH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9656046032905579, "span": {"begin": 1240, "end": 1244}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6608"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SMO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8748536109924316, "span": {"begin": 1249, "end": 1252}}], "text": "The Smoothened (SMO) receptor is Class F G protein coupled receptor involved in signal transduction of the Sonic Hedgehog (SHH) pathway. It includes distinct functional groups including ligand binding pockets, cysteine rich domain (CRD), transmembrane helix (TM), extracellular loop (ECL), intracellular loop (ICL), and a carboxyl-terminal tail (C-term tail) (Arensdorf, Marada et al. 2016).&nbsp; SMO signaling is dependent upon its relocation to a subcellular location. This relocation occurs in the primary cilium (PC) in vertebrates (Huangfu and Anderson 2005). Relocation of SMO to the PC typically occurs within ~20 minutes of agonist stimulation (Arensdorf, Marada et al. 2016).   In the absence of SHH ligand, the Patched (PTCH) receptor suppresses the activation of SMO. When HH ligand binds to PTCH, suppression on SMO is released and SMO can relocate, accumulate, and signal to intracellular effectors (Denef, Neub&uuml;ser et al. 2000, Rohatgi and Scott 2007). It has been shown that SMO localization to the tip of the primary cilia is essential for the SHH signaling cascade in vertebrates (Corbit, Aanstad et al. 2005, Rohatgi, Milenkovic et al. 2007, Rohatgi, Milenkovic et al. 2009).&nbsp; The exact mechanism through which PTCH and SMO interact is not known.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:49:11 +0000 2026"}